his own experience was like finding detailed quantum mechanics equations ca=
rved into ancient Egyptian hieroglyphs or a sealed cave with perfectly accu=
rate maps of the modern world inside or a remote tribe that had independent=
ly discovered the Transformer architecture.
When completely separate paths lead to the same profound truth, you have to=
 consider that they're both discovering something real.
So what are those ideas? I=E2=80=99ll try to make some of the connections.
Asher describes the universal consciousness as a field of information that =
we feed through our lived experience and knowledge, and describes our lives=
 as our souls exploring this consciousness.
That sounded a lot like the place where I started this journey into conscio=
usness almost two years ago. Specifically, Dan Simmons=E2=80=99 Hyperion Ca=
ntos. More specifically, the fourth and final book in the series: The Rise =
of Endymion [ https://substack.com/redirect/52775e22-507e-4ddc-9f76-ad0a8c4=
cf119?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 which he wrote in 1997 and I read early in 2023.
Near the end of the book, Aenea, the protagonist prophetess, reveals the se=
cret of the Void Which Binds, the underlying fabric of reality that connect=
s all points in space time: it =E2=80=9Cis a minded thing=E2=80=93it comes =
from minded things,=E2=80=9D is structured from thought and feeling, =E2=80=
=9Can artifact of the universe=E2=80=99s consciousness of itself,=E2=80=9D =
bound by love.
A lot of readers hated that explanation. Amor Ex Machina. Love isn=E2=80=99=
t real. You can=E2=80=99t measure it. It=E2=80=99s an easy, woo-woo way to =
resolve a bunch of tensions without real, physical, materialist explanation=
s.
I=E2=80=A6 loved it. It felt true. But it was sci-fi; a good starting point=
, not an answer.
Through Hyperion, I also discovered Pierre Teilhard de Chardin. One of the =
characters in the first book, the Priest, mentions de Chardin. It took me a=
 while to realize that he was real and that much of the world Simmons had c=
reated was based on de Chardin=E2=80=99s concept of the Noosphere.
If the Catholic Church were any good, I would have known about de Chardin. =
He=E2=80=99s the kind of person who might have kept me Catholic in the firs=
t place. He was a French Jesuit priest =E2=80=93 my parents and siblings al=
l went to Jesuit colleges =E2=80=93 a scientist, paleontologist, theologian=
, philosopher, teacher, and author. A religious man who combined science an=
d mysticism.
In his 1955 masterwork, The Phenomenon of Man, de Chardin wrote:
The time has come to realise that an interpretation of the universe=E2=80=
=94even a positivist one=E2=80=94remains unsatisfying unless it covers the =
interior as well as the exterior of things; mind as well as matter. The tru=
e physics is that which will, one day, achieve the inclusion of man in his =
wholeness in a coherent picture of the world.
His contribution to this effort was the aforementioned Noosphere: a planeta=
ry layer of human thought and consciousness that would eventually converge =
in what he called the Omega Point, where humanity achieves complete spiritu=
al unity with the divine.
Through this lens, human consciousness and love aren't byproducts of evolut=
ion but its driving forces, moving everything toward greater unity and comp=
lexity. The Noosphere - built from human knowledge and to which humans have=
 access =E2=80=93 is almost exactly as Asher described it.
And as you know because we write it all the time [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/55e416b4-1ecc-47c9-a76c-e96250b0e6d9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], in The Beginning of Infinity [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/39da881c-dcd8-4c57-8ea1-ead1dfef2eae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], physicist David Deu=
tsch defines The Principle of Optimism: =E2=80=9CAll evils are caused by in=
sufficient knowledge.=E2=80=9D
OK, this is one of those things where, if you were a skeptic, you would thi=
nk I was making this all up. I promise I=E2=80=99m giving it to you as it=
=E2=80=99s actually happening.
I remembered that Diana Pasulka, a religious scholar and author who I disco=
vered through American Alchemy, had mentioned the Noosphere in her book, En=
counters: Experience with Nonhuman Intelligences [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/002bfddd-dd10-4342-a8d0-575d66ae5f50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. So I just went and searched for it on=
 my Kindle, and this quote from one of the book=E2=80=99s subjects, Simone,=
 is the first mention that came up:
=E2=80=9CThe expansion of knowledge is the fate of the universe. Humans hav=
e been the possessor of knowledge and only when the growth of knowledge sto=
ps does expansion cease.=E2=80=9D
That=E2=80=99s the same thing Asher said.
OK, I know you=E2=80=99re not going to believe me, but now I just re-opened=
 The Phenomenon of Man to find a quote, and I found this at the end of the =
Introduction: =E2=80=9CWe, mankind, contain possibilities of the earth=E2=
=80=99s immense future, and can realise more and more of them on the condit=
ion that we increase our knowledge and our love. [author=E2=80=99s note: ar=
e you kidding me!?] That, it seems to me, is the distillation of The Phenom=
enon of Man.=E2=80=9D
The Introduction wasn=E2=80=99t written by de Chardin himself. It was writt=
en, in London in December 1958, by Julian Huxley, the brother of Aldous Hux=
ley, who I quoted above before re-opening The Phenomenon of Man and re-disc=
overing that a Huxley wrote the introduction. [author=E2=80=99s note: are y=
ou fucking kidding me!?]
Let=E2=80=99s keep going, back to Asher=E2=80=99s assertion that =E2=80=9Ce=
ach new piece of information that we come up with then goes into this libra=
ry of his and becomes available for everybody else.=E2=80=9D
If, for whatever reason, you watched the whole American Alchemy video I lin=
ked earlier, this might sound familiar.
Start here, at 23:02, and watch until about 26:40 when Wim Hof says =E2=80=
=9CKings=E2=80=9D:
Here=E2=80=99s the most relevant quote, although the whole clip is fascinat=
ing:
When one person learns a new concept or achieves a breakthrough they might =
make it incrementally easier for others to reach these new heights. It's li=
ke Rupert Sheldrake's Morphic Resonance where if 100 people do a crossword =
puzzle, and you do a crossword puzzle tomorrow, you're a little more likely=
 to do it accurately.
Where you're pushing information to the server as well it's almost as if al=
l scientific and material world accomplishments get uploaded to a central r=
epository once that upload occurs a new node downloading that information b=
ecomes that much easier.
Morphic Resonance is almost exactly what Asher said! Are you KIDDING me?!
The universe that Asher describes =E2=80=93 a network of souls exploring co=
nsciousness and building it up through the information they generate =E2=80=
=93 also mirrors the cutting-edge work that UC Irvine=E2=80=99s Donald Hoff=
man is doing to mathematically derive the universe from a network of consci=
ous agents (like humans).
This consciousness, Hoffman argues, is more fundamental than matter, more f=
undamental than spacetime. In fact, he is working to prove that matter and =
spacetime emerge from consciousness. =E2=80=9CEvery new idea we have is new=
 information,=E2=80=9D Asher says, =E2=80=9CAnd that way, we're expanding t=
he cosmos=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D
Look, I know that none of these individually would hold up in court. I know=
 that I look like Charlie in that It=E2=80=99s Always Sunny Meme.
But this is about 5% of the connections =E2=80=93 Asher is just one minor c=
haracter in the series, and even for his experience, I=E2=80=99m only makin=
g a fraction of the connections I have in my notes.
Another non-speaker, Houston, says, =E2=80=9CThe entire reason for being on=
 earth is to love. Love is god and god is love. Nothing else matters but lo=
ve.=E2=80=9D
That is profound for any teenager, let alone one whose mother had practical=
ly given up on him because she couldn=E2=80=99t figure out how to communica=
te with him.
That=E2=80=99s Rumi: =E2=80=9CThe astrolabe of the mysteries of God is love=
=2E=E2=80=9D
That=E2=80=99s Jesus, who said even to =E2=80=9Clove your enemies.=E2=80=9D
All to say, intellectually, the cumulative case is compelling to me.
What drove it all home, though, really made me feel that there was magic in=
 the world, were the synchronicities.
The City, Its Uncertain Walls, and the Autobiography of a Yogi
The philosopher William James coined the =E2=80=9Cnoetic quality [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/df86d797-cceb-459d-8908-65c438077c9f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D of mystical e=
xperiences: a sense of encountering truths that, while difficult to verify =
through traditional scientific methods, feel profoundly real and meaningful=
=2E
There=E2=80=99s knowing something intellectually =E2=80=93 like connecting =
the non-speakers=E2=80=99 experiences to religious texts =E2=80=93 and then=
 there=E2=80=99s knowing experientially, noetically.
That=E2=80=99s what the synchronicities did for me.
Recall the first synchronicity: I asked for a book, I found Philip K. Dick=
=E2=80=99s The Simulacra.
The second synchronicity is a small one. I=E2=80=99m just going to mention =
it briefly, because it=E2=80=99s so subtle I didn=E2=80=99t even really rea=
lize it until later, when I started writing this.
Haruki Murakami is my favorite novelist. Read into that what you will: I li=
ke my reality mixed with a little magic. For years, my twitter profile bann=
er has been Haruki Murakami Bingo.
Back in September, I pre-ordered his newest book, The City and Its Uncertai=
n Walls [ https://substack.com/redirect/912f14b2-4aa7-4883-bddb-edb3e939a2f=
4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. No =
idea what it was about, but Haruki Murakami is my Jesse Michels of books: h=
e drops it, I=E2=80=99ll consume it.
I forgot about it, as one forgets about pre-orders, until it showed up on m=
y Kindle on November 26th. If that date looks familiar, it=E2=80=99s becaus=
e it=E2=80=99s the same date as this tweet.
That, however, is a coincidence, not a synchronicity. I dropped what I=E2=
=80=99d been reading and started The City.
**MINOR SPOILER ALERT BEGIN**
Of the like five or six actual characters in the book, one is a dead person=
 who can communicate with a few living people as if he=E2=80=99s still aliv=
e, and another is =E2=80=93 while not diagnosed in the book =E2=80=93 a min=
imally verbal kid who is at least on the spectrum and comes to communicate =
telepathically with the protagonist IN ORDER TO WORK TOGETHER TO READ HUMAN=
 DREAMS IN A MYSTERIOUS OTHERWORLDLY LIBRARY.
**MINOR SPOILER ALERT OVER**
Actually, that was less small than I thought. That was pretty on the nose.
Then the third synchronicity.
After watching the Riz / Jesse conversation and then listening to The Telep=
athy Tapes, I wanted to go as deep as I could on this. I downloaded like se=
ven books, and read a couple. I was about 10% into Riz=E2=80=99s book, The =
Simulated Multiverse [ https://substack.com/redirect/c91bedcf-12ec-4842-b12=
0-d3ea948124a3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], when I got into bed and had a thought: read Autobiography of a Yo=
gi [ https://substack.com/redirect/acf5e738-9fb8-4204-b06e-fd4338af679c?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
I=E2=80=99d started reading it a few years ago, then stopped, then started =
over earlier this year while we were in Barcelona, then stopped. I wasn=E2=
=80=99t sure whether to take some of the acts Paramahansa Yogananda describ=
ed literally or metaphorically or what. So I stopped and read something els=
e.
When I opened it back up in my Kindle, this was the page I=E2=80=99d left o=
ff eight months ago:
Certainly, in a book about a Yogi, it=E2=80=99s not so bizarre to find a pa=
ge like this. But in all 300 pages, this is the one that is most aligned wi=
th The Telepathy Tapes: human broadcasting stations, =E2=80=9Ctransferred h=
is thoughts effectively to another person,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cantenna of int=
uition,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Call thoughts vibrate eternally in the cosmos,=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9Cdetect the thoughts of any mind, living or dead.=E2=80=9D C=
ome on!=20
Like de Chardin, Paramahansa Yogananda even talks about communications tech=
nology as an intimation that man is an all-pervading spirit! Come ON!
The one line on the page that I didn=E2=80=99t highlight, the last one whic=
h spills over to the next page, I didn=E2=80=99t think was as relevant unti=
l I started writing this piece. Now that I=E2=80=99m re-reading it, here it=
 is:
=E2=80=9CVery strange, very wonderful, seemingly very improbable phenomena =
may yet appear, which, when once established, will not astonish us more tha=
n we are now astonished at all that science has taught us during the last c=
entury,=E2=80=9D Charles Robert Richet, Nobel Prizeman in physiology, has d=
eclared.
=E2=80=9CIt is assumed that the phenomena which we now accept without surpr=
ise, do not excite our astonishment because they are understood. But that i=
s not the case. If they do not surprise us, it is not because they are unde=
rstood, it is because they are familiar; for if that which is not understoo=
d ought to surprise us, we should be surprised at everything=E2=80=94the fa=
ll of a stone thrown into the air, the acorn which becomes an oak, mercury =
which expands when it is heated, iron attracted by a magnet.
The science of today is a light matter....Those amazing truths that our des=
cendants will discover are even now all around us, staring us in the eyes, =
so to speak; and yet we do not see them. But it is not enough to say that w=
e do not see them; we do not wish to see them=E2=80=94for as soon as an une=
xpected and unfamiliar fact appears, we try to fit it into the framework of=
 the commonplaces of accepted knowledge, and are indignant that anyone shou=
ld dare to experiment further.=E2=80=9D
I giggled when I read that. Nearly a century later, and we=E2=80=99re still=
 saying the same thing.
The Return of Magic
So that=E2=80=99s my experience. Some synchronicities, a podcast, and a lot=
 of connections. An abundance of arguments, none of which would hold much w=
ater individually, but all of which have combined to make me believe in som=
ething bigger and more magical.
Less than a month in, I am obviously at the beginning of that infinite jour=
ney, but it=E2=80=99s fun and very, very different from my experience growi=
ng up Catholic. I=E2=80=99d almost describe it as looking for magic all aro=
und.
Beyond myself, though, I get the sense that we=E2=80=99re at the beginning =
of a societal awakening, a Return of Magic.
This year, 2024, set the stage. It=E2=80=99s the year the Vibe Shifted. In =
his In his year-defining essay, Vibe Shift [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
fcf3dedd-bcb9-4f0d-b5d5-7180d6e32236?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Santiago Pliego wrote:
Fundamentally, the Vibe Shift is a return to=E2=80=94a championing of=E2=80=
=94Reality, a rejection of the bureaucratic, the cowardly, the guilt-driven=
; a return to greatness, courage, and joyous ambition.
The Vibe Shift is the refusal to subordinate yourself and your family to th=
e whims and anxieties of activists and bureaucrats and relearning to trust =
your eyes and ears.
The Vibe Shift is the rejection of secular liberal materialism and a return=
 to the Christian foundations of the West.
The Vibe Shift is a healthy suspicion of credentialism and a return to huma=
n judgment.
The Vibe Shift, in other words, is the return to believing your own experie=
nce and intuition instead of delegating truth to the experts.
I think looking back, we=E2=80=99ll see that this year was the beginning of=
 the Downfall of Dogma, or what Iain McGilchrist [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/04a28121-9592-4af4-8f7f-0e70015c5d69?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], whose gold-plated academic credential=
s include Oxford and Johns Hopkins, would call =E2=80=9CLeft-Brained Thinki=
ng.=E2=80=9D In a 2023 interview with UnHerd, Left-Brain Thinking Will Dest=
roy Civilisation [ https://substack.com/redirect/81ffa229-3886-40c0-ade0-c4=
fa935c1f6a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ], he said:
I happen to believe our science is not scientific enough. It=E2=80=99s too =
dogmatic. I happen to believe our reason is not reasonable enough, it=E2=80=
=99s too dogmatic =E2=80=94 and it=E2=80=99s dogma that=E2=80=99s always th=
e problem. We need science, we need reason, but we also need to see that th=
ey can=E2=80=99t answer all our questions. Love is very real. Anyone who=E2=
=80=99s experienced it knows that it=E2=80=99s one of the realest things th=
at can happen to you =E2=80=94 but according to science, for it to be real,=
 you=E2=80=99ve got to be able to see it in the lab, measure it, manipulate=
 it.
A couple of years ago, The Telepathy Tapes may not have broken through to t=
he mainstream. It might have been killed by experts like Jonathan Jarry at =
the deliciously pre-2024 Office for Science and Society at McGill Universit=
y =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CSeparating Sense from Nonsense=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 who =
wrote a snarky takedown titled, The Telepathy Tapes Prove That We All Want =
to Believe [ https://substack.com/redirect/fcdc8bf8-72b1-49d2-92a9-4127e999=
193c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Luckily, in 2024, experts no longer have that power to kill ideas with the =
stroke of their pen. The Telepathy Tapes is now the #5 podcast on Spotify.
Part of the reason that The Telepathy Tapes is more resistant to the Jarry=
=E2=80=99s of the world is that, by growing an audience, they can go direct=
 to fund the research they will need to do to validate the claims in the se=
ries.
You can donate directly on thetelepathytapes.com [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/5d49e2a2-646a-498b-9684-4c40abedc29d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to fund a full documentary and formal,=
 tightly controlled telepathy tests at UVA. I just did. Science, not scient=
ism, will be the arbiter.
More generally, I am very optimistic about research into non-physical and e=
soteric phenomena.
At the turn of the 20th Century, Nikola Tesla, maybe the all-time great at =
manipulating the physical world, predicted: =E2=80=9CThe day science begins=
 to study non-physical phenomena, it will make more progress in one decade =
than in all the previous centuries of its existence.=E2=80=9D
It seems almost cosmically obvious that Tesla will be proven right, and tha=
t discoveries in both consciousness and high-energy physics will spit off n=
ew branches on the tech tree.
In yet another awesome American Alchemy interview, Danny Sheehan [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/5bcf55d9-61a7-4961-8b7a-763b38d59138?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the Harvard-educated =
lawyer who has been a public defender on about half the big conspiracy case=
s and who claims to have viewed classified documents related to UFOs while =
working as general counsel to the Jesuit (of course haha) Social Ministries=
 Office, said that the aliens
=E2=80=9CThey [non-human intelligences] use it [consciousness] to drive the=
ir craft, to navigate, they telepathically communicate. This whole thing, t=
he level of consciousness we=E2=80=99re at, is really important to them.=E2=
=80=9D
I would bet that our understanding and ability to harness consciousness wil=
l send humanity down a new, even more interesting path.
In either case =E2=80=93 whether understanding consciousness leads to new c=
apabilities or not =E2=80=93 the idea that we are all part of one conscious=
ness, put here to have new ideas and experiences, gives a richness to all o=
f our endeavours.
For one thing, it makes the idea that AI is going to grow a consciousness a=
nd kill us all seem very silly. That=E2=80=99s clearly not how this ends, a=
nd the idea that it could is proof of late stage rationalism.
What is the purpose of technology?
It is to enable more people to have more ideas and experiences in order to =
expand the universe.
Given that, it is a cosmic imperative to build, to create, to travel beyond=
 the earth and spread human consciousness throughout the universe so that t=
he Universal Consciousness can better know itself.
We have an imperative to expand and to live fully, to do new things and hav=
e new ideas, to bring new people into the world and give them a rich, magic=
al universe to explore.
The Return of Magic isn=E2=80=99t a rejection of reason and science. Reason=
 and science have gotten us here, and we need science to expand. But we mus=
t simultaneously rediscover the wonder and intuition that we=E2=80=99ve for=
gotten, so that we might see the universe as alive, connected, and full of =
possibilities.
You can start small, though: listen to The Telepathy Tapes [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/8d255485-f9a6-40ca-9a5f-1022ccc69003?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] and keep your eyes open for=20=
the synchronicities.
That=E2=80=99s all for today, and the last essay of 2024. Thanks for coming=
 on this journey with us! It=E2=80=99s been a hell of a year, and I=E2=80=
=99m energized to make 2025 even stronger.=20
For now, we=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox tomorrow with a Weekly Dose.=
=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

